      <part part_index="3" name="Water-storing Himalaya Tower" page="0" source="2">
      	<article allWordsNum="270">
            	<![CDATA[
If you have at least one full glass of clean drinking water, you are lucky. According to the World Water Council (世界水理事会), one out of six people in the world do not have clean water to drink.
Based on Wikipedia (维基百科), about 40 percent of the world's fresh water is stored within 55,000 glaciers (冰川). These glaciers are located high in the Himalayan Mountains.
Lately, however, the Himalayan glaciers and those in other parts of the world have been decreasing because of global warming. And the glaciers are estimated to disappear by the year 2162.
The question is: how do we get the water out?
Just imagine a water tower (水塔) located on the top of the Himalayan Mountains. It can supply water to half of the world's population. Some students from Harbin Institute of Technology (哈尔滨工业大学) have designed such a massive (巨型的) structure called the "Himalaya Water Tower."
Looking like something straight out of The Lord of the Rings (《指环王》), the "Himalaya Water Tower" collects water, purifies (净化) it, and stores it as ice for future use.
The tower looks like a big plant and mainly consists of four parts. The lower part is used for collecting water during the rainy season, while the upper part, above the snow line (雪线), is the place to store ice. Similar to a plant's roots, the tower also contains pipes to transport water to nearby towns and villages.
The Himalaya Water Tower concept won the 2012 Skyscraper competition (摩天大厦设计竞赛) held by eVolo magazine, and it may be a solution to water problems caused by the melting (融化) of glaciers in the world's tallest mountains. If replicated (复制) in numbers, this innovative (创新的) tower could someday provide fresh water for future generations.
       	]]>
            </article>
